article.headline: Gophers go without a shot for 3:26, fall to OSU
article.linkText: Minnesota goes without a shot for 3:26, falls to OSU
article.story:
COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Minnesota rolled into town leading the nation in scoring and shooting, averaging almost 80 points per game and shooting 53 percent.

But for 3 minutes and 26 seconds, Minnesota (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) couldn't score Thursday night. In fact, the Gophers couldn't even get a shot
off, and Ohio State (No. 25 AP) capitalized, using defense and athleticism to win 66-58.

"We lost the game tonight in three minutes,'' Golden Gophers
(16-4, 5-4 Big Ten) guard Lindsay Whalen said. 

Kim Wilburn and Courtney Coleman each scored 18 points as the Buckeyes (16-5, 7-3) used a late run to blow the game open.

Coleman said the Buckeyes knew the Gophers' weakness.

"We knew our post players could outrun their post players,'' Coleman said.

They did so in the second half. Coleman scored 14 points in the second half, six of them in transition.

With the game tied at 39 with about 12 minutes to play, LaToya
Turner, Coleman and Caity Matter took over for the Buckeyes.

Turner made two free throws and converted a three-point play,
Coleman made two free throws and a layup, Matter hit a jumper and a
3-pointer and Coleman made two more free throws as the Buckeyes
used a 16-4 run to move ahead 55-43 and take control. The Buckeyes
held Minnesota scoreless from 6:27 to 3:11.

After a timeout, Shannon Bolden scored to stop the run, but Ohio
State came right back with a jumper by D'Wan Shackleford and
back-to-back fast-break layups by Coleman and Matter to make it
61-45 with 1:58 to play.
	
The Gophers tried to mount a comeback, but seemingly every time
they scored, an Ohio State player would respond with an easy layup
or free throws after being fouled on a breakaway.

Ohio State coach Jim Foster said the key to the game was simple.

"We got out in transition and Caity started to make some good
reads on screens,'' Foster said.

Foster said the Buckeyes knew they couldn't bang with the bigger
Gophers.

   "You can't let them dictate position,'' Foster said. "You've
got to move.''

And move they did. Ohio State scored 15 points on fast breaks
and didn't allow the Gophers a fast-break point.

"I could just feel the momentum of Ohio State that last seven
or eight minutes,'' Minnesota coach Pam Borton said. "They were a
completely different team.''

Janel McCarville led Minnesota with 15 points and 12 rebounds, 
while Corrin Von Wald added 12 points. Matter had 14 for Ohio State.

Without Whalen, who sat out most of the first half with two
fouls, the Gophers struggled, repeatedly taking tough shots and
turning the ball over. Whalen scored two points in the first half,
making a pair of free throws in place of Corrin Von Wald, who was
hurt on a fast break when she was fouled hard by Matter.

The Buckeyes weren't much better. Ohio State turned it over 12
times in the first half and struggled for consistency on offense.

The Gophers said they knew they had the Buckeyes frustrated, but
didn't capitalize.

"That's where we should have stomped on them right away,'' said
Von Wald.

Instead, Wilburn bailed the Buckeyes out, scoring 12 points in
the first half, including her first 3-pointer of the season as the
first-half buzzer sounded. No other Ohio State player had more than
five points in the first half.

The Gophers led 22-21 with 1:45 to play. Kim Prince made
back-to-back jumpers in the lane and Janel McCarville made a short
jumper to give the Gophers a 28-21 lead before Wilburn hit her 3-pointer.
